acred feminine. At the same time, it charts a new direction for finding a truly egalitarian vision of God and human relations through a feminist-ecological spirituality. Rosemary Radford Ruether begins her exploration of the divine feminine with an analysis of prehistoric archaeology that challenges the popular idea that, until their overthrow by male-dominated monotheism, many ancient societies were matriarchal in structure, governed by a feminine divinity and existing in harmony with nature. For Ruether, the historical evidence suggests the reality about these societies is much more complex. She goes on to consider key myths and rituals from Sumerian, Babylonian, Egyptian, and Anatolian cultures; to examine the relationships among gender, deity, and nature in the Hebrew religion; and to discuss the development of Mariology and female mysticism in medieval Catholicism, and the continuation of Wisdom mysticism in Protestanism. She also gives a provocative analysis of the meeting of Aztec and Christian female symbols in Mexico and of today's neo-pagan movements in the United States.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aGoddess religion. 0aGoddesses. 0aWomen and religion. 7aRELIGION / Comparative Religion.2bisacsh  aancient matriarchy.  aaztec religions.  ababylonia.  achristianity.  acomparative religions.  adeity.  adivine feminine.  aegypt.  afemale mysticism.  afeminine divinity.  afemininity.  afeminist ecological spirituality.  agender studies.  agoddess movements.  agoddesses.  ajudaism.  amariology.  amatriarchal structures.  amedieval catholicism.  amedieval religious literature.  amyths and rituals.  areligion.  asacred female imagery.  asacred feminine.  aspiritual.  asumerian.  awestern civilization.  awestern culture.  awestern religions.08iTitle i